nese jazz pianists]]\n[[Category:Japanese lyricists]]\n[[Category:Japanese male musicians]]\n[[Category:Japanese musicians]]\n[[Category:Japanese writers]]\n[[Category:Kwansei Gakuin University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male jazz composers]]\n[[Category:The New School alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Slimyfrog", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor grammar edits and restructuring of sentences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Senri_Oe"}
{"title_page": "Diane Johnson", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name             = Diane Johnson\n| embed            = \n| honorific_prefix = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| image_upright    = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = Diane Lain\n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym        = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1934|4|28}}\n| birth_place      = [[Moline, Illinois|Moline]], [[Illinois]], United States\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| occupation       = \n| language         = English\n| residence        = \n| nationality      = [[Americans|American]]\n| citizenship      = United States\n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| period           = \n| genres           = [[Fiction]], [[satire]], [[essay]]s, [[screenwriting]]\n| subject          = <!-- or: | subjects = -->\n| movement         = \n| notableworks     = <!-- or: | notablework = -->\n| spouse           = <!-- or: | spouses = -->\n| partner          = <!-- or: | partners = -->\n| children         = \n| relatives        = \n| awards           = American Academy of Arts and Letters, 1999\n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| years_active     = \n| module           = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} -->\n| portaldisp       = <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc; or omit -->\n}}\n'''Diane Johnson''', born '''Diane Lain''' (April 28, 1934), is an American [[novelist]] and [[list of essayists|essayist]] whose [[satire|satirical]] novels often feature American heroines living abroad in contemporary France. She was a finalist for the Pulitzer Prize for her novel ''Persian Nights'' in 1988.\n\n==Career==\nBorn Diane Lain in [[Moline, Illinois|Moline]], [[Illinois]], Johnson has authored books including ''Lulu in Marrakech'' (2008), ''L'Affaire'' (2003), ''Le Mariage'' (2000) and ''[[Le Divorce (novel)|Le Divorce]]'' (1997), for which she was a [[National Book Award]] finalist and the winner of the [[California Book Awards|California Book Award]] gold medal for fiction. Her memoir ''Flyover Lives'' was released in  January 2014.\n\nShe has been a frequent contributor to ''[[The New York Review of Books]]'' since the mid-1970s. With filmmaker [[Stanley Kubrick]], Johnson co-authored the screenplay to ''[[The Shining (film)|The Shining]]'' (1980), based on the [[horror fiction|horror]] novel of the same name by [[Stephen King]].<ref name=NYT>{{cite web|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=Audio Interview: Diane Johnson|author=Goldstein, Bill|date=March 7, 2000|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/00/04/16/specials/johnson-audio.html}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, ''[[Le Divorce]]'', a film adaptation of her [[comedy of manners]] novel of the same name, was released, directed by [[James Ivory (director)|James Ivory]] and starred [[Kate Hudson]] and [[Naomi Watts]].<ref name=NYT2>{{cite web|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=FILM REVIEW; Paris in the Summer, When It Sits There|authorlink=A. O. Scott|author=Scott, A. O.|date=August 8, 2003|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9407EFD71731F93BA3575BC0A9659C8B63}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nJohnson attended [[Stephens College]], a small women's college in Missouri. In her sophomore year she entered the ''[[Mademoiselle (magazine)|Mademoiselle]]'' magazine Guest Editor contest and was selected as one of 20 women from across the United States to work on the magazine for a month in New York City in 1953. The month at the magazine would prove to be formative in her eventual career as a writer. Another member of the group was [[Sylvia Plath]] who would write about the experience in her novel ''[[The Bell Jar]]''. \n\nJohnson shadowed the Health and Beauty editor and was responsible for answering readers' questions about makeup. In a piece she wrote for the September 2003 edition of ''Vogue'' magazine, Johnson said, \"I still have a strong memory of Plath's white straw beret, her blonde pageboy and cheerful face. (None of us understood the anguish of her secret life, though maybe the editors did, for they treated her carefully, the one most destined to succeed.)\" \n\nIn the ''Vogue'' article, Johnson wrote the month at ''Mademoiselle'' and her exposure to Plath taught her a key lesson. \"I realized that if you took pains with your writing, you could make art, and that the rather facile little stories I had dashed off for my English classes or the school magazine were probably not art. It was, in fact, the example of \"Sunday at the Mintons',\" Sylvia Plath's winning story in the Guest Editor contest, that made that point to me and changed my life, though not immediately.\" \n\nJohnson went on to say, \"Writing was a serious form of work, and to be serious, like those New York editors, you had to send in your stories. Writers and editors were embarked on a consequential enterprise, the business of literature and books. What happiness to have been taught that lesson; I did send in my novels.\"\n\nThat same year, 1953, Johnson married B. Lamar Johnson Jr.. Within eight years, she had given birth to four children with him: Kevin, Darcy, Amanda, and Simon. In the ''Vogue'' article she wrote, \"Novel-writing would become my refuge during moments snatched during their naps and play visits. New York..came to symbolize a road not taken, but I was not sorry, exactly, for if I had stayed in New York, I probably would not have done my writing.\"\n\nAfter separating from and divorcing Johnson, in 1968 she married John Frederic Murray, a physician who became chief of pulmonary and critical care at [[San Francisco General Hospital]]. Since his retirement, they have divided their time between homes in San Francisco and in [[Paris]], where Murray died of [[Covid-19]] in March 2020 at the age of 92.<ref>{{cite news |first=Sam |last=Whiting |url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/Dr-John-Murray-former-SF-General-physician-15157429.php |title=Dr. John Murray, former SF General physician, killed by COVID-19 complications |newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |date=March 25, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Novels===\n*''Fair Game'' (1965)\n*''Loving Hands at Home'' (1968)\n*''Burning'' (Dutton, 1971)\n*''The Shadow Knows'' (Dutton, 1974)\n*''Lying low'' (Knopf, 1978)\n*''Persian Nights'' (Knopf, 1987)\n*''Health and Happiness'' (Knopf, 1990)\n*''[[Le Divorce (novel)|Le Divorce]]'' (Dutton, 1997)\n*''Le Mariage'' (Dutton, 2000)\n*''L'Affaire'' (Dutton, 2003)\n*''Lulu in Marrakech'' (Dutton, 2008)\n\n===Non-fiction===\n*''The True History of Mrs. Meredith and Other Lesser Lives'' (Knopf, 1972)\n*''Dashiell Hammett: A Life'' (1983)\n*''Natural Opium: Some Travelers' Tales'' (Knopf, 1993)\n*''Terrorists and Novelists: Essays'' (Knopf, 1982)\n*''Into a Paris Quartier: Reine Margot's Chapel and Other Haunts of St.-Germain'' (National Georgraphic Directions, 2005)\n*''Flyover Lives: A Memoir'' (Viking, 2014)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/story/2008/11/28/ST2008112801518.html The Writing Life: By Diane Johnson - washingtonpost.com]\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/04/25/AR2008042503097.html The Dollar's Down. But We're Not Out. By Diane Johnson - washingtonpost.com]\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/fashion/stellamagazine/3354982/La-vraie-Franandccedilaise.html La vraie Fran\u00e7aise By Diane Johnson - Telegraph]\n* {{IMDb name|id=0424956|title=Diane Johnson}}\n* [http://research.hrc.utexas.edu:8080/hrcxtf/view?docId=ead/00165.xml&query=johnson,%20diane&query-join=and Diane Johnson Collection] at the [[Harry Ransom Center]] at the [[University of Texas at Austin]]\n* [http://www.nybooks.com/authors/129 Diane Johnson author page and archive] from ''The New York Review of Books''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johnson, Diane}}\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Moline, Illinois]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American satirists]]\n[[Category:Members of the American Academy of Arts and Letters]]\n[[Category:Writers from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Writers from Paris]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Illinois]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:French women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Women essayists]]\n[[Category:Women satirists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Illinois]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Comedians from California]]\n[[Category:20th-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name             = Diane Johnson\n| embed            = \n| honorific_prefix = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| image_upright    = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = Diane Lain\n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym        = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1934|4|28}}\n| birth_place      = [[Moline, Illinois|Moline]], [[Illinois]], United States\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| occupation       = \n| language         = English\n| residence        = \n| nationality      = [[Americans|American]]\n| citizenship      = United States\n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| period           = \n| genres           = [[Fiction]], [[satire]], [[essay]]s, [[screenwriting]]\n| subject          = <!-- or: | subjects = -->\n| movement         = \n| notableworks     = <!-- or: | notablework = -->\n| spouse           = <!-- or: | spouses = -->\n| partner          = <!-- or: | partners = -->\n| children         = \n| relatives        = \n| awards           = American Academy of Arts and Letters, 1999\n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| years_active     = \n| module           = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} -->\n| portaldisp       = <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc; or omit -->\n}}\n'''Diane Johnson''', born '''Diane Lain''' (April 28, 1934), is an American [[novelist]] and [[list of essayists|essayist]] whose [[satire|satirical]] novels often feature American heroines living abroad in contemporary France. She was a finalist for the Pulitzer Prize for her novel ''Persian Nights'' in 1988.\n\n==Career==\nBorn Diane Lain in [[Moline, Illinois|Moline]], [[Illinois]], Johnson's books include ''Lulu in Marrakech'' (2008), ''L'Affaire'' (2003), ''Le Mariage'' (2000) and ''[[Le Divorce (novel)|Le Divorce]]'' (1997), for which she was a [[National Book Award]] finalist and the winner of the [[California Book Awards|California Book Award]] gold medal for fiction. Her memoir ''Flyover Lives'' was released in  January 2014.\n\nShe has been a frequent contributor to ''[[The New York Review of Books]]'' since the mid-1970s. With filmmaker [[Stanley Kubrick]], Johnson co-authored the screenplay to ''[[The Shining (film)|The Shining]]'' (1980), based on the [[horror fiction|horror]] novel of the same name by [[Stephen King]].<ref name=NYT>{{cite web|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=Audio Interview: Diane Johnson|author=Goldstein, Bill|date=March 7, 2000|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/00/04/16/specials/johnson-audio.html}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, ''[[Le Divorce]]'', a film adaptation of her [[comedy of manners]] novel of the same name, was released, directed by [[James Ivory (director)|James Ivory]] and starred [[Kate Hudson]] and [[Naomi Watts]].<ref name=NYT2>{{cite web|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=FILM REVIEW; Paris in the Summer, When It Sits There|authorlink=A. O. Scott|author=Scott, A. O.|date=August 8, 2003|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9407EFD71731F93BA3575BC0A9659C8B63}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nJohnson attended [[Stephens College]], a small women's college in Missouri. In her sophomore year she entered the ''[[Mademoiselle (magazine)|Mademoiselle]]'' magazine Guest Editor contest and was selected as one of 20 women from across the United States to work on the magazine for a month in New York City in 1953. The month at the magazine would prove to be formative in her eventual career as a writer. Another member of the group was [[Sylvia Plath]] who would write about the experience in her novel ''[[The Bell Jar]]''. \n\nJohnson shadowed the Health and Beauty editor and was responsible for answering readers' questions about makeup. In a piece she wrote for the September 2003 edition of ''Vogue'' magazine, Johnson said, \"I still have a strong memory of Plath's white straw beret, her blonde pageboy and cheerful face. (None of us understood the anguish of her secret life, though maybe the editors did, for they treated her carefully, the one most destined to succeed.)\" \n\nIn the ''Vogue'' article, Johnson wrote the month at ''Mademoiselle'' and her exposure to Plath taught her a key lesson. \"I realized that if you took pains with your writing, you could make art, and that the rather facile little stories I had dashed off for my English classes or the school magazine were probably not art. It was, in fact, the example of \"Sunday at the Mintons',\" Sylvia Plath's winning story in the Guest Editor contest, that made that point to me and changed my life, though not immediately.\" \n\nJohnson went on to say, \"Writing was a serious form of work, and to be serious, like those New York editors, you had to send in your stories. Writers and editors were embarked on a consequential enterprise, the business of literature and books. What happiness to have been taught that lesson; I did send in my novels.\"\n\nThat same year, 1953, Johnson married B. Lamar Johnson Jr.. Within eight years, she had given birth to four children with him: Kevin, Darcy, Amanda, and Simon. In the ''Vogue'' article she wrote, \"Novel-writing would become my refuge during moments snatched during their naps and play visits. New York..came to symbolize a road not taken, but I was not sorry, exactly, for if I had stayed in New York, I probably would not have done my writing.\"\n\nAfter separating from and divorcing Johnson, in 1968 she married John Frederic Murray, a physician who became chief of pulmonary and critical care at [[San Francisco General Hospital]]. Since his retirement, they have divided their time between homes in San Francisco and in [[Paris]], where Murray died of [[Covid-19]] in March 2020 at the age of 92.<ref>{{cite news |first=Sam |last=Whiting |url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/Dr-John-Murray-former-SF-General-physician-15157429.php |title=Dr. John Murray, former SF General physician, killed by COVID-19 complications |newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |date=March 25, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Novels===\n*''Fair Game'' (1965)\n*''Loving Hands at Home'' (1968)\n*''Burning'' (Dutton, 1971)\n*''The Shadow Knows'' (Dutton, 1974)\n*''Lying low'' (Knopf, 1978)\n*''Persian Nights'' (Knopf, 1987)\n*''Health and Happiness'' (Knopf, 1990)\n*''[[Le Divorce (novel)|Le Divorce]]'' (Dutton, 1997)\n*''Le Mariage'' (Dutton, 2000)\n*''L'Affaire'' (Dutton, 2003)\n*''Lulu in Marrakech'' (Dutton, 2008)\n\n===Non-fiction===\n*''The True History of Mrs. Meredith and Other Lesser Lives'' (Knopf, 1972)\n*''Dashiell Hammett: A Life'' (1983)\n*''Natural Opium: Some Travelers' Tales'' (Knopf, 1993)\n*''Terrorists and Novelists: Essays'' (Knopf, 1982)\n*''Into a Paris Quartier: Reine Margot's Chapel and Other Haunts of St.-Germain'' (National Georgraphic Directions, 2005)\n*''Flyover Lives: A Memoir'' (Viking, 2014)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/story/2008/11/28/ST2008112801518.html The Writing Life: By Diane Johnson - washingtonpost.com]\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/04/25/AR2008042503097.html The Dollar's Down. But We're Not Out. By Diane Johnson - washingtonpost.com]\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/fashion/stellamagazine/3354982/La-vraie-Franandccedilaise.html La vraie Fran\u00e7aise By Diane Johnson - Telegraph]\n* {{IMDb name|id=0424956|title=Diane Johnson}}\n* [http://research.hrc.utexas.edu:8080/hrcxtf/view?docId=ead/00165.xml&query=johnson,%20diane&query-join=and Diane Johnson Collection] at the [[Harry Ransom Center]] at the [[University of Texas at Austin]]\n* [http://www.nybooks.com/authors/129 Diane Johnson author page and archive] from ''The New York Review of Books''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johnson, Diane}}\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Moline, Illinois]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American satirists]]\n[[Category:Members of the American Academy of Arts and Letters]]\n[[Category:Writers from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Writers from Paris]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Illinois]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:French women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Women essayists]]\n[[Category:Women satirists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Illinois]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Comedians from California]]\n[[Category:20th-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n", "name_user": "Saharawiki", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:fixed grammatical dangler~~~~~", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diane_Johnson"}
{"title_page": "Jamal Adams", "text_new": "{{short description|American football strong safety}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name = Jamal Adams\n| image = Jamal Adams.JPG\n| image_size = 225px\n| caption = Adams in the 2017 NFL season\n| alt = \n| number = 33\n| current_team = New York Jets\n| position = [[Safety (gridiron football position)|Strong safety]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1995|10|17}}\n| birth_place = [[Lewisville, Texas]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 0\n| weight_lbs = 213\n| high_school = [[Hebron High School (Texas)|Hebron]] ([[Carrollton, Texas]])\n| college = [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]]\n| draftyear = 2017\n| draftround = 1\n| draftpick = 6\n| pastteams = \n* [[New York Jets]] ({{NFL Year|2017}}\u2013present)\n| status = Active\n| highlights = \n* 2\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2019 Pro Bowl|2018]], [[2020 Pro Bowl|2019]])\n* First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2019 All-Pro Team|2019]])\n* Second-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2018 All-Pro Team|2018]])\n* [[PFWA All-Rookie Team]] ([[PFWA All-Rookie Team#2017|2017]])\n* Second-team [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[2016 College Football All-America Team|2016]])\n* First-team All-[[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] ([[2016 All-SEC football team|2016]])\n* Second-team All-[[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] ([[2015 All-SEC football team|2015]])\n| statweek = 17\n| statseason = 2019\n| statlabel1 = [[Tackle (football move)|Total tackles]] \n| statvalue1 = 273\n| statlabel2 = [[Quarterback sacks|Sacks]]\n| statvalue2 = 12.0\n| statlabel3 = [[Fumble|Forced fumbles]] \n| statvalue3 = 6\n| statlabel4 = [[Fumble|Fumble recoveries]]\n| statvalue4 = 3\n| statlabel5 = [[Interceptions]] \n| statvalue5 = 2\n| statlabel6 = [[Touchdown|Defensive touchdowns]]\n| statvalue6 = 2\n| nflnew = jamaladams/2557979\n| pfr = A/AdamJa00\n}}\n\n'''Jamal Lee Adams''' (born October 17, 1995) is an [[American football]] [[Safety (gridiron football position)|strong safety]] for the [[New York Jets]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He played [[college football]] at [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]], and was drafted sixth overall in the [[2017 NFL Draft]] by the Jets.\n\n==Early years==\nAdams attended [[Hebron High School (Texas)|Hebron High School]] in [[Carrollton, Texas]]. During his final two years, he had 138 tackles and seven [[interceptions]] on defense and 20 [[touchdowns]] on offense. In his senior year, Hebron finished 8\u20134 on the season, advancing to the [[University Interscholastic League|UIL]] 5A Division II Area final at [[AT&T Stadium]], where they lost 42\u201321 to [[Cedar Hill High School|Cedar Hill]].<ref>{{cite news |title=No vacancy: Lodge, Cedar Hill keep Hebron out of third round of playoffs |first=Justin |last=Thomas |work=Carrollton Leader |date=November 24, 2013 |url=http://starlocalmedia.com/carrolltonleader/sports/no-vacancy-lodge-cedar-hill-keep-hebron-out-of-third/article_1301fac8-54da-11e3-8959-0019bb2963f4.html }}</ref>\n\nAdams was rated by [[Scout.com]] as a five star recruit and was ranked among the top ten overall recruits in his class.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jamal Adams, New York Jets, Safety |url=https://247sports.com/Player/Jamal-Adams-13171/ |website=247Sports |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> He committed to [[Louisiana State University]] (LSU) to play [[college football]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Holland |first1=EJ |title=5-star Hebron safety Jamal Adams commits to LSU over Florida: 'I'm ready to go win some national championships' |url=http://collegesportsblog.dallasnews.com/2014/01/5-star-hebron-safety-jamal-adams-commits-to-lsu-over-florida-im-ready-to-go-win-some-national-championships.html/ |website=The Dallas Morning News |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118041546/http://collegesportsblog.dallasnews.com/2014/01/5-star-hebron-safety-jamal-adams-commits-to-lsu-over-florida-im-ready-to-go-win-some-national-championships.html/ |archivedate=November 18, 2015 |date=January 2, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Dellenger |first1=Ross |title=Surprise, Les: Jamal Adams commits to LSU |url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_12d5d0a7-4c40-5222-83ff-bbaa1d98baf7.html |website=The Advocate |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=January 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nAdams played in all 13 games with two starts as a true freshman at LSU in 2014 and had 66 tackles and a [[Quarterback sack|sack]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ching |first1=David |title=Early success has helped LSU's Jamal Adams grab starting spot |url=https://www.espn.com/blog/ncfnation/post/_/id/109260/early-success-has-helped-lsus-jamal-adams-grab-starting-spot |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=March 16, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Higgins |first1=Ron |title=LSU safety Jamal Adams hits anything that moves: Ron Higgins |url=https://www.nola.com/sports/article_05174b76-6b0b-5515-b16b-f5130fee83bc.html |website=NOLA.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=August 26, 2015}}</ref> As a sophomore, he was a second-team All-[[Southeastern Conference]] selection as a safety by the [[Associated Press]] (AP) and SEC coaches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collegefootball.ap.org/article/2015-associated-press-all-sec-football-team|title=2015 Associated Press All-SEC football team|agency=Associated Press|work=College Football|date=December 14, 2015|accessdate=November 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Kalland|first1=Robby|title=2015 Coaches' All-SEC Team: Alabama leads the way with 10 selections|url=http://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/2015-coaches-all-sec-team-alabama-leads-the-way-with-10-selections/|accessdate=November 2, 2016|publisher=CBS Sports|date=December 8, 2015}}</ref> As a junior, Adams was named to the AP All-SEC first team.<ref>{{cite news|title=It's a Sweep: No 1. Alabama Cleans up on AP All-SEC Team|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Sports/wireStory/sweep-alabama-cleans-ap-sec-team-44064709|accessdate=December 10, 2016|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ABC News|date=December 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn January 6, 2017, Adams announced that he would forgo his senior season and enter the [[2017 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|URL=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000770432/article/lsus-jamal-adams-declares-his-intention-to-enter-the-nfl-draft| title=LSU's Jamal Adams declares his intention to enter 2017 NFL Draft| accessdate=January 6, 2017| website=NFL.com| author=Chase Goodbread| date=January 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===College statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n! rowspan=\"2\"|GP\n! colspan=\"5\"|Defense\n|-\n! Tackles !! Loss !! Sck !! Int !! FF\n|-\n! [[2014 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2014]] !! [[2014 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]]\n| 12 || 66 || 5.0 || 1.0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! [[2015 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2015]] !! [[2015 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]]\n| 12 || 67 || 5.5 || 0.0 || 4 || 1\n|-\n! [[2016 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2016]] !! [[2016 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]]\n| 12 || 76 || 7.5 || 1.0 || 1 || 1\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Career !! 36 !! 209 !! 18.0 !! 2.0 !! 5 !! 2\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\nComing out of college, Adams was invited to the [[NFL Combine]] and performed all the required drills. On May 4, 2017, Adams attended LSU's pro day and opted to run the 40-yard dash (4.40s), 20-yard dash (2.57s), and 10-yard dash (1.58s) and was able to improve on his combine numbers. He was projected to be a first round pick by the majority of analysts and scouts. ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', DraftScout.com, [[Pro Football Focus]], and [[ESPN]] ranked Adams the top safety in the draft.<ref>{{cite web|URL=https://www.si.com/2017-nfl-draft-position-rankings| title=2017 NFL draft rankings: Top prospects by position| accessdate=May 16, 2017| website=si.com| author=Chris Burke| date=April 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|URL=https://www.profootballfocus.com/draft-college-football-top-32-prospects-for-the-2017-nfl-draft/| title=Top 32 Prospects For the 2017 NFL Draft| accessdate=May 16, 2017| website=profootballfocus.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/draft2017/story/_/id/19180310/ranking-top-100-prospects-available-2017-nfl-draft-espn-nfl-nation-reporter-jeff-legwold| title=Ranking the Top 100 Prospects| accessdate=May 16, 2017| website=ESPN.com| author=Jeff Legwold| date=April 22, 2017}}</ref>\n{{external media\n| video1 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-combine/0ap3000000796862/Jamal-Adams-2017-Combine-Workout Jamal Adams' NFL Combine workout]\n| video2 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-combine/0ap3000000790631/Jamal-Adams-runs-an-official-4-56-40-yard-dash Jamal Adams' 40-yard dash]\n| video3 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-draft/0ap3000000797920/Jamal-Adams-runs-40-yard-dash-at-LSU-Pro-Day Adams' 40-yard dash at LSU Pro Day]\n}}\n\nHE IS THE PREZ\n\n\n\n{{NFL predraft\n| height ft = 5\n| height in = 11\u00be\n| weight = 214\n| dash = 4.56\n| ten split = 1.60\n| twenty split = 2.67\n| shuttle = 4.13\n| cone drill = 6.96\n| vertical = 31\u00bd\n| broad ft = 10\n| broad in = 0\n| bench = 18\n| wonderlic = \n| arm span = 33\u215c\n| hand span = 9\u00bc\n| note = All values from 2017 NFL Combine.<ref>{{cite web |title=NFL Events: Combine Player Profiles - Jamal Adams |url=http://www.nfl.com/combine/profiles/jamal-adams?id=2557979 |website=NFL.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=*Jamal Adams, DS #1 SS, LSU |url=http://www.draftscout.com/dsprofile.php?PlayerId=130736&DraftYear=2017 |website=draftscout.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe [[New York Jets]] selected Adams with the sixth overall pick in the [[2017 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Jets select LSU safety Jamal Adams with sixth pick|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000803350/article/jets-select-lsu-safety-jamal-adams-with-sixth-pick|author=Sessler, Marc|website=NFL.com|date=April 27, 2017}}</ref> He was the first defensive back selected in 2017.\n{{external media\n| video1 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-draft/0ap3000000803366/Jets-select-Jamal-Adams-No-6-in-the-2017-NFL-Draft Jets select Jamal Adams sixth overall]\n| video2 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-draft/0ap3000000799645/Jamal-Adams-2017-NFL-Draft-profile Jamal Adams draft profile]\n}}\n\n===2017===\nOn July 20, 2017, the Jets signed Adams to a fully guaranteed four-year, [[United States dollar|$]]22.25 million contract that included a $14.32 million [[signing bonus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Jamal Adams finalizes rookie deal with Jets|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/blog/new-york-jets/post/_/id/69790/agent-no-1-pick-jamal-adams-finalizes-deal-with-jets|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jets' rookie safeties Adams, Maye looking more like vets|url=http://www.sanluisobispo.com/sports/article166373992.html|publisher=The Turbine|accessdate=July 31, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810053838/http://www.sanluisobispo.com/sports/article166373992.html|archive-date=August 10, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=Spotrac.com: Jamal Adams contract| url=http://www.spotrac.com/nfl/new-york-jets/jamal-adams-21747/| accessdate=April 7, 2018| website=Spotrac.com}}</ref>\n\nAdams entered training camp competing against [[Calvin Pryor]] and fellow rookie [[Marcus Maye]] for a role as a starting safety.<ref>{{cite web| title=Jets' Todd Bowles says Calvin Pryor better not be afraid of competition |url=https://www.all22.com/new-york-jets/jets-coach-todd-bowles-calvin-pryor-better-not-afraid-competition/ |access-date=April 7, 2018| website=all22.com| author=Barbato, Matt| date=May 7, 2017}}</ref> Head coach [[Todd Bowles]] named Adams the starting strong safety to begin the regular season, alongside free safety Maye.<ref>{{cite web| title=The Jets Opening Day Depth Chart| url=https://www.ganggreennation.com/platform/2017/9/5/16256228/the-jets-opening-day-depth-chart| accessdate=April 7, 2018| website=ganggreennation| date=September 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAdams made his professional regular season debut and first career start in the Jets season-opener versus the [[2017 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]] and recorded five combined tackles and deflected a pass in a 21\u201312 loss. Adams made his first career tackle on running back [[Mike Tolbert]] after his 13-yard run on the Bills' first drive.<ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Game Center: Week1-2017: New York Jets @ Buffalo Bills| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/jamaladams/2557979/gamelogs| accessdate=April 7, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref> On September 24, Adams recorded two solo tackles, broke up a pass, and made his first career sack on quarterback [[Jay Cutler (American football)|Jay Cutler]] during a 20\u20136 win against the [[2017 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]].<ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Game Center: Week 3-2017: Miami Dolphins @ New York Jets| url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2017092408/2017/REG3/dolphins@jets| accessdate=April 7, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref> In Week 17, he collected a season-high ten combined tackles (three solo) and a pass deflection in the Jets' 26\u20136 loss to the [[2017 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]].<ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: Jamal Adams (2017)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/jamaladams/2557979/gamelogs| accessdate=April 7, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref> Adams finished his rookie season in {{NFL Year|2017}} with 83 combined tackles (63 solo), six pass deflections, and two sacks in 16 games and 16 starts.<ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: Jamal Adams (career)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/jamaladams/2557979/careerstats| accessdate=April 7, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\nAdams was named a captain on the Jets' roster for the [[2018 NFL season|2018 season]]. He got his first career interception off of [[Matt Cassel]] at the Jets' season opener versus the [[2018 Detroit Lions season|Detroit Lions]]. The Jets ultimately won the game 48\u201317.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cimini |first1=Rich |title=Jets LB on Matt Stafford: 'We knew his signals; we knew everything' |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/24639497/new-york-jets-say-defense-knew-matthew-stafford-signals-rout |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=September 11, 2018 |quote=Claiborne, Jamal Adams and Trumaine Johnson also made interceptions. For Adams, the 2017 first-round pick, it was the first of his career.}}</ref> Adams finished his second season with 115 tackles, 3.5 sacks, 3 forced fumbles with 1 recovered fumble, and 1 interception and started all 16 games.\n\nOn December 18, Adams was named a [[2019 Pro Bowl|Pro Bowl]] selection for the first time in his career.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Allen |first1=Eric |title=Jamal Adams Is Pro Bowl Bound |url=https://www.newyorkjets.com/news/jamal-adams-is-pro-bowl-bound |website=newyorkjets.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> Adams was named Defensive MVP of the game.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lange |first1=Randy |title=Jamal Adams Named Defensive MVP in AFC Pro Bowl Win |url=https://www.newyorkjets.com/news/jamal-adams-named-defensive-mvp-in-afc-pro-bowl-win |website=newyorkjets.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=January 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Jets' Jamal Adams wins Defensive MVP Award in Pro Bowl |url=https://www.sny.tv/jets/news/jets-jamal-adams-wins-defensive-mvp-award-in-pro-bowl/303229798/ |website=SNY |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=January 27, 2019}}</ref> Adams became viral after an incident where he tackled the [[2018 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]] mascot at a 2019 Pro Bowl practice. This was due to the fierce rivalry of the [[Jets\u2013Patriots rivalry|Jets and Patriots]. Adams apologized and let the Patriots mascot tackle him back.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gardner |first1=Steve |title=Jets' Jamal Adams crushes Patriots mascot at Pro Bowl event, says he was 'just having fun' |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2019/01/24/jets-jamal-adams-tackles-patriots-mascot-hospitalized/2669326002/ |website=USA TODAY |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAdams was also named Second-team AP All-Pro during this season. On December 28, Adams was named Curtis Martin Team MVP.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lange |first1=Randy |title=Jamal Adams Named Jets' 2018 Curtis Martin Team MVP |url=https://www.newyorkjets.com/news/jamal-adams-named-jets-2018-curtis-martin-team-mvp |website=newyorkjets.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=December 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019===\nBefore the [[2019 NFL season|2019 season]], Adams was ranked at 37th place as part of the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2019|NFL Top 100 2019]] list.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jamal Adams Named No. 37 on NFL Top 100 List |url=https://www.newyorkjets.com/news/jamal-adams-named-no-37-on-nfl-top-100-list |website=newyorkjets.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=July 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn September 18, 2019, Adams was fined $21,000 for a hit he made on [[Baker Mayfield]] on ''[[Monday Night Football]]'' against the [[2019 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]] in Week 2.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bergman |first1=Jeremy |title=NFL confirms Jets' Jamal Adams will be fined for late hit |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001056654/article/nfl-confirms-jets-jamal-adams-will-be-fined-for-late-hit |website=NFL.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=September 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Abdeldaiem |first1=Alaa |title=Jamal Adams Says NFL is 'a Damn Joke' After Being Fined for Hit on Baker Mayfield |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2019/09/19/jets-jamal-adams-rips-league-fine-hit-baker-mayfield-browns |website=Sports Illustrated |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=September 18, 2019}}</ref> In Week 3 versus the [[2019 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]], Adams recorded a 61-yard pick six off rookie quarterback [[Jarrett Stidham]] in the 30\u201314 loss. This was Adams' first interception of the season and his first career pick six.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127861 |title=Brady, Patriots defense shine in 30-14 win over Jets |date=September 22, 2019 |website=espn.com |access-date=September 22, 2019}}</ref> On October 10, Adams had his previous fine rescinded after winning an appeal.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Patra |first1=Kevin |title=Jamal Adams wins appeal of fine for hit on Mayfield |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001064167/article/jamal-adams-wins-appeal-of-fine-for-hit-on-mayfield |website=NFL.com |accessdate=October 10, 2019 |date=October 10, 2019}}</ref> In Week 10 against the [[2019 New York Giants season|New York Giants]], Adams recorded a team-high nine tackles and sacked [[Daniel Jones (American football)|Daniel Jones]] twice, one of which was a strip sack that he forced and returned for a 25-yard touchdown, as the Jets won 34\u201327 win.<ref>{{cite web |title=Eww York: Darnold, Jets hold on to beat Jones, Giants 34-27 |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127952 |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=November 10, 2019 |date=November 10, 2019}}</ref> He was named the AFC Defensive Player of the Week for his performance.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bergman |first1=Jeremy |title=Jamal Adams, Jadeveon Clowney among Players of the Week |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001076380/article/jamal-adams-jadeveon-clowney-among-players-of-the-week |website=NFL.com |accessdate=November 13, 2019 |date=November 13, 2019}}</ref> During Week 11 versus the [[2019 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]], Adams finished with three sacks as the Jets won 34\u201317.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sam Darnold throws 4 TD passes, Jets rout Redskins 34-17 |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128086 |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=November 17, 2019}}</ref> During a game versus the [[2019 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]], Adams suffered an ankle injury at the start of the game.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Vasquez |first1=Andy |title=NY Jets' Jamal Adams emotional after suffering foot injury in loss to Bengals |url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/sports/nfl/jets/2019/12/01/ny-jets-jamal-adams-emotional-after-suffering-injury-bengals-loss/4331362002/ |website=North Jersey |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=December 1, 2019}}</ref> He played the entire game and had to miss the next two weeks due to this injury. He came back from his injury in Week 16 against the [[2019 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]] in the Jets' 16\u201310 win.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lange |first1=Randy |title=Jamal Adams, Marcus Maye, Jets D Win the Battle vs. the Steelers |url=https://www.newyorkjets.com/news/jamal-adams-marcus-maye-jets-d-win-the-battle-vs-the-steelers |website=newyorkjets.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=December 22, 2019}}</ref> At the end of the season, he was named to his second consecutive Pro Bowl and was honored with his first career First-Team AP selection.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Landis |first1=Olivia |title=Jamal Adams Is Pro Bowl Bound For a Second Consecutive Year |url=https://www.newyorkjets.com/news/jamal-adams-is-pro-bowl-bound-for-a-second-consecutive-year |website=newyorkjets.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=December 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Greenberg |first1=Ethan |title=Jets S Jamal Adams Named First Team All-Pro |url=https://www.newyorkjets.com/news/jets-s-jamal-adams-named-first-team-all-pro |website=newyorkjets.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=January 3, 2020}}</ref> Adams also earned his second Curtis Martin Team MVP for the second straight year.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lange |first1=Randy |title=Jamal Adams Receives 2nd Consecutive Curtis Martin Team MVP Award |url=https://www.newyorkjets.com/news/jamal-adams-receives-2nd-consecutive-curtis-martin-team-mvp-award |website=newyorkjets.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=December 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Regular season===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n! colspan=\"2\"|Games\n! colspan=\"4\"|Tackles\n! colspan=\"6\"|Interceptions\n! colspan=\"2\"|Fumbles\n|-\n! GP !! GS !! Comb !! Solo !! Ast !! Sck !! PDef !! Int !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! FF !! FR\n|-\n! [[2017 NFL season|2017]] !! [[2017 New York Jets season|NYJ]]\n| 16 || 16 || 83 || 63 || 20 || 2.0 || 6 || \u2014 || \u2014 || 0.0 || \u2014 || \u2014 || 1 || 2\n|-\n! [[2018 NFL season|2018]] !! [[2018 New York Jets season|NYJ]]\n| 16 || 16 || 115 || 86 || 29 || 3.5 || 12 || 1 || 38 || 38.0 || 38 || 0 || 3 || 1\n|-\n! [[2019 NFL season|2019]] !! [[2019 New York Jets season|NYJ]]\n| 14 || 14 || 75 || 61 || 14 || 6.5 || 7 || 1 || 61 || 61.0 || 61T || 1 || 2 || 1\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Career !! 46 !! 46 !! 273 !! 210 !! 63 !! 12.0 !! 25 !! 2 !! 99 !! 49.5 !! 61 !! 1 !! 6 !! 4\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\nHis father, running back [[George Adams (American football)|George Adams]], played in the [[National Football League]] (NFL) from 1985 to 1991.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rodrigue |first1=Marcus |last2=Mickles |first2=Sheldon |last3=Rabalais |first3=Scott |title=New York connections: LSU safety Jamal Adams has some |url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_18cd519d-2025-57cc-a392-b255def92185.html |website=The Advocate |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=October 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Footballstats |nfl=2557979 |pfr=A/AdamJa00}}\n* [http://www.lsusports.net/ViewArticle.dbml?ATCLID=209392663 LSU Tigers bio]\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{New York Jets roster navbox}}\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{2017 NFL Draft}}\n{{JetsFirstPick}}\n{{Jets2017DraftPicks}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adams, Jamal}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football safeties]]\n[[Category:LSU Tigers football players]]\n[[Category:New York Jets players]]\n[[Category:People from Carrollton, Texas]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Texas]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from the Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football strong safety}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name = Jamal Adams\n| image = Jamal Adams.JPG\n| image_size = 225px\n| caption = Adams in the 2017 NFL season\n| alt = \n| number = 33\n| current_team = New York Jets\n| position = [[Safety (gridiron football position)|Strong safety]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1995|10|17}}\n| birth_place = [[Lewisville, Texas]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 0\n| weight_lbs = 213\n| high_school = [[Hebron High School (Texas)|Hebron]] ([[Carrollton, Texas]])\n| college = [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]]\n| draftyear = 2017\n| draftround = 1\n| draftpick = 6\n| pastteams = \n* [[New York Jets]] ({{NFL Year|2017}}\u2013present)\n| status = Active\n| highlights = \n* 2\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2019 Pro Bowl|2018]], [[2020 Pro Bowl|2019]])\n* First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2019 All-Pro Team|2019]])\n* Second-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2018 All-Pro Team|2018]])\n* [[PFWA All-Rookie Team]] ([[PFWA All-Rookie Team#2017|2017]])\n* Second-team [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[2016 College Football All-America Team|2016]])\n* First-team All-[[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] ([[2016 All-SEC football team|2016]])\n* Second-team All-[[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] ([[2015 All-SEC football team|2015]])\n| statweek = 17\n| statseason = 2019\n| statlabel1 = [[Tackle (football move)|Total tackles]] \n| statvalue1 = 273\n| statlabel2 = [[Quarterback sacks|Sacks]]\n| statvalue2 = 12.0\n| statlabel3 = [[Fumble|Forced fumbles]] \n| statvalue3 = 6\n| statlabel4 = [[Fumble|Fumble recoveries]]\n| statvalue4 = 3\n| statlabel5 = [[Interceptions]] \n| statvalue5 = 2\n| statlabel6 = [[Touchdown|Defensive touchdowns]]\n| statvalue6 = 2\n| nflnew = jamaladams/2557979\n| pfr = A/AdamJa00\n}}\n\n'''Jamal Lee Adams''' (born October 17, 1995) is an [[American football]] [[Safety (gridiron football position)|strong safety]] for the [[New York Jets]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He played [[college football]] at [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]], and was drafted sixth overall in the [[2017 NFL Draft]] by the Jets.\n\n==Early years==\nAdams attended [[Hebron High School (Texas)|Hebron High School]] in [[Carrollton, Texas]]. During his final two years, he had 138 tackles and seven [[interceptions]] on defense and 20 [[touchdowns]] on offense. In his senior year, Hebron finished 8\u20134 on the season, advancing to the [[University Interscholastic League|UIL]] 5A Division II Area final at [[AT&T Stadium]], where they lost 42\u201321 to [[Cedar Hill High School|Cedar Hill]].<ref>{{cite news |title=No vacancy: Lodge, Cedar Hill keep Hebron out of third round of playoffs |first=Justin |last=Thomas |work=Carrollton Leader |date=November 24, 2013 |url=http://starlocalmedia.com/carrolltonleader/sports/no-vacancy-lodge-cedar-hill-keep-hebron-out-of-third/article_1301fac8-54da-11e3-8959-0019bb2963f4.html }}</ref>\n\nAdams was rated by [[Scout.com]] as a five star recruit and was ranked among the top ten overall recruits in his class.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jamal Adams, New York Jets, Safety |url=https://247sports.com/Player/Jamal-Adams-13171/ |website=247Sports |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> He committed to [[Louisiana State University]] (LSU) to play [[college football]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Holland |first1=EJ |title=5-star Hebron safety Jamal Adams commits to LSU over Florida: 'I'm ready to go win some national championships' |url=http://collegesportsblog.dallasnews.com/2014/01/5-star-hebron-safety-jamal-adams-commits-to-lsu-over-florida-im-ready-to-go-win-some-national-championships.html/ |website=The Dallas Morning News |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118041546/http://collegesportsblog.dallasnews.com/2014/01/5-star-hebron-safety-jamal-adams-commits-to-lsu-over-florida-im-ready-to-go-win-some-national-championships.html/ |archivedate=November 18, 2015 |date=January 2, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Dellenger |first1=Ross |title=Surprise, Les: Jamal Adams commits to LSU |url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_12d5d0a7-4c40-5222-83ff-bbaa1d98baf7.html |website=The Advocate |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=January 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nAdams played in all 13 games with two starts as a true freshman at LSU in 2014 and had 66 tackles and a [[Quarterback sack|sack]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ching |first1=David |title=Early success has helped LSU's Jamal Adams grab starting spot |url=https://www.espn.com/blog/ncfnation/post/_/id/109260/early-success-has-helped-lsus-jamal-adams-grab-starting-spot |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=March 16, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Higgins |first1=Ron |title=LSU safety Jamal Adams hits anything that moves: Ron Higgins |url=https://www.nola.com/sports/article_05174b76-6b0b-5515-b16b-f5130fee83bc.html |website=NOLA.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=August 26, 2015}}</ref> As a sophomore, he was a second-team All-[[Southeastern Conference]] selection as a safety by the [[Associated Press]] (AP) and SEC coaches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collegefootball.ap.org/article/2015-associated-press-all-sec-football-team|title=2015 Associated Press All-SEC football team|agency=Associated Press|work=College Football|date=December 14, 2015|accessdate=November 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Kalland|first1=Robby|title=2015 Coaches' All-SEC Team: Alabama leads the way with 10 selections|url=http://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/2015-coaches-all-sec-team-alabama-leads-the-way-with-10-selections/|accessdate=November 2, 2016|publisher=CBS Sports|date=December 8, 2015}}</ref> As a junior, Adams was named to the AP All-SEC first team.<ref>{{cite news|title=It's a Sweep: No 1. Alabama Cleans up on AP All-SEC Team|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Sports/wireStory/sweep-alabama-cleans-ap-sec-team-44064709|accessdate=December 10, 2016|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ABC News|date=December 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn January 6, 2017, Adams announced that he would forgo his senior season and enter the [[2017 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|URL=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000770432/article/lsus-jamal-adams-declares-his-intention-to-enter-the-nfl-draft| title=LSU's Jamal Adams declares his intention to enter 2017 NFL Draft| accessdate=January 6, 2017| website=NFL.com| author=Chase Goodbread| date=January 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===College statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n! rowspan=\"2\"|GP\n! colspan=\"5\"|Defense\n|-\n! Tackles !! Loss !! Sck !! Int !! FF\n|-\n! [[2014 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2014]] !! [[2014 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]]\n| 12 || 66 || 5.0 || 1.0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! [[2015 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2015]] !! [[2015 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]]\n| 12 || 67 || 5.5 || 0.0 || 4 || 1\n|-\n! [[2016 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2016]] !! [[2016 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]]\n| 12 || 76 || 7.5 || 1.0 || 1 || 1\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Career !! 36 !! 209 !! 18.0 !! 2.0 !! 5 !! 2\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\nComing out of college, Adams was invited to the [[NFL Combine]] and performed all the required drills. On May 4, 2017, Adams attended LSU's pro day and opted to run the 40-yard dash (4.40s), 20-yard dash (2.57s), and 10-yard dash (1.58s) and was able to improve on his combine numbers. He was projected to be a first round pick by the majority of analysts and scouts. ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', DraftScout.com, [[Pro Football Focus]], and [[ESPN]] ranked Adams the top safety in the draft.<ref>{{cite web|URL=https://www.si.com/2017-nfl-draft-position-rankings| title=2017 NFL draft rankings: Top prospects by position| accessdate=May 16, 2017| website=si.com| author=Chris Burke| date=April 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|URL=https://www.profootballfocus.com/draft-college-football-top-32-prospects-for-the-2017-nfl-draft/| title=Top 32 Prospects For the 2017 NFL Draft| accessdate=May 16, 2017| website=profootballfocus.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/draft2017/story/_/id/19180310/ranking-top-100-prospects-available-2017-nfl-draft-espn-nfl-nation-reporter-jeff-legwold| title=Ranking the Top 100 Prospects| accessdate=May 16, 2017| website=ESPN.com| author=Jeff Legwold| date=April 22, 2017}}</ref>\n{{external media\n| video1 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-combine/0ap3000000796862/Jamal-Adams-2017-Combine-Workout Jamal Adams' NFL Combine workout]\n| video2 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-combine/0ap3000000790631/Jamal-Adams-runs-an-official-4-56-40-yard-dash Jamal Adams' 40-yard dash]\n| video3 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-draft/0ap3000000797920/Jamal-Adams-runs-40-yard-dash-at-LSU-Pro-Day Adams' 40-yard dash at LSU Pro Day]\n}}\n\n{{NFL predraft\n| height ft = 5\n| height in = 11\u00be\n| weight = 214\n| dash = 4.56\n| ten split = 1.60\n| twenty split = 2.67\n| shuttle = 4.13\n| cone drill = 6.96\n| vertical = 31\u00bd\n| broad ft = 10\n| broad in = 0\n| bench = 18\n| wonderlic = \n| arm span = 33\u215c\n| hand span = 9\u00bc\n| note = All values from 2017 NFL Combine.<ref>{{cite web |title=NFL Events: Combine Player Profiles - Jamal Adams |url=http://www.nfl.com/combine/profiles/jamal-adams?id=2557979 |website=NFL.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=*Jamal Adams, DS #1 SS, LSU |url=http://www.draftscout.com/dsprofile.php?PlayerId=130736&DraftYear=2017 |website=draftscout.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe [[New York Jets]] selected Adams with the sixth overall pick in the [[2017 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Jets select LSU safety Jamal Adams with sixth pick|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000803350/article/jets-select-lsu-safety-jamal-adams-with-sixth-pick|author=Sessler, Marc|website=NFL.com|date=April 27, 2017}}</ref> He was the first defensive back selected in 2017.\n{{external media\n| video1 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-draft/0ap3000000803366/Jets-select-Jamal-Adams-No-6-in-the-2017-NFL-Draft Jets select Jamal Adams sixth overall]\n| video2 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-draft/0ap3000000799645/Jamal-Adams-2017-NFL-Draft-profile Jamal Adams draft profile]\n}}\n\n===2017===\nOn July 20, 2017, the Jets signed Adams to a fully guaranteed four-year, [[United States dollar|$]]22.25 million contract that included a $14.32 million [[signing bonus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Jamal Adams finalizes rookie deal with Jets|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/blog/new-york-jets/post/_/id/69790/agent-no-1-pick-jamal-adams-finalizes-deal-with-jets|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jets' rookie safeties Adams, Maye looking more like vets|url=http://www.sanluisobispo.com/sports/article166373992.html|publisher=The Turbine|accessdate=July 31, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810053838/http://www.sanluisobispo.com/sports/article166373992.html|archive-date=August 10, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=Spotrac.com: Jamal Adams contract| url=http://www.spotrac.com/nfl/new-york-jets/jamal-adams-21747/| accessdate=April 7, 2018| website=Spotrac.com}}</ref>\n\nAdams entered training camp competing against [[Calvin Pryor]] and fellow rookie [[Marcus Maye]] for a role as a starting safety.<ref>{{cite web| title=Jets' Todd Bowles says Calvin Pryor better not be afraid of competition |url=https://www.all22.com/new-york-jets/jets-coach-todd-bowles-calvin-pryor-better-not-afraid-competition/ |access-date=April 7, 2018| website=all22.com| author=Barbato, Matt| date=May 7, 2017}}</ref> Head coach [[Todd Bowles]] named Adams the starting strong safety to begin the regular season, alongside free safety Maye.<ref>{{cite web| title=The Jets Opening Day Depth Chart| url=https://www.ganggreennation.com/platform/2017/9/5/16256228/the-jets-opening-day-depth-chart| accessdate=April 7, 2018| website=ganggreennation| date=September 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAdams made his professional regular season debut and first career start in the Jets season-opener versus the [[2017 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]] and recorded five combined tackles and deflected a pass in a 21\u201312 loss. Adams made his first career tackle on running back [[Mike Tolbert]] after his 13-yard run on the Bills' first drive.<ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Game Center: Week1-2017: New York Jets @ Buffalo Bills| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/jamaladams/2557979/gamelogs| accessdate=April 7, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref> On September 24, Adams recorded two solo tackles, broke up a pass, and made his first career sack on quarterback [[Jay Cutler (American football)|Jay Cutler]] during a 20\u20136 win against the [[2017 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]].<ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Game Center: Week 3-2017: Miami Dolphins @ New York Jets| url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2017092408/2017/REG3/dolphins@jets| accessdate=April 7, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref> In Week 17, he collected a season-high ten combined tackles (three solo) and a pass deflection in the Jets' 26\u20136 loss to the [[2017 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]].<ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: Jamal Adams (2017)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/jamaladams/2557979/gamelogs| accessdate=April 7, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref> Adams finished his rookie season in {{NFL Year|2017}} with 83 combined tackles (63 solo), six pass deflections, and two sacks in 16 games and 16 starts.<ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: Jamal Adams (career)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/jamaladams/2557979/careerstats| accessdate=April 7, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\nAdams was named a captain on the Jets' roster for the [[2018 NFL season|2018 season]]. He got his first career interception off of [[Matt Cassel]] at the Jets' season opener versus the [[2018 Detroit Lions season|Detroit Lions]]. The Jets ultimately won the game 48\u201317.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cimini |first1=Rich |title=Jets LB on Matt Stafford: 'We knew his signals; we knew everything' |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/24639497/new-york-jets-say-defense-knew-matthew-stafford-signals-rout |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=September 11, 2018 |quote=Claiborne, Jamal Adams and Trumaine Johnson also made interceptions. For Adams, the 2017 first-round pick, it was the first of his career.}}</ref> Adams finished his second season with 115 tackles, 3.5 sacks, 3 forced fumbles with 1 recovered fumble, and 1 interception and started all 16 games.\n\nOn December 18, Adams was named a [[2019 Pro Bowl|Pro Bowl]] selection for the first time in his career.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Allen |first1=Eric |title=Jamal Adams Is Pro Bowl Bound |url=https://www.newyorkjets.com/news/jamal-adams-is-pro-bowl-bound |website=newyorkjets.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=December 18, 2018}}</ref> Adams was named Defensive MVP of the game.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lange |first1=Randy |title=Jamal Adams Named Defensive MVP in AFC Pro Bowl Win |url=https://www.newyorkjets.com/news/jamal-adams-named-defensive-mvp-in-afc-pro-bowl-win |website=newyorkjets.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=January 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Jets' Jamal Adams wins Defensive MVP Award in Pro Bowl |url=https://www.sny.tv/jets/news/jets-jamal-adams-wins-defensive-mvp-award-in-pro-bowl/303229798/ |website=SNY |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=January 27, 2019}}</ref> Adams became viral after an incident where he tackled the [[2018 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]] mascot at a 2019 Pro Bowl practice. This was due to the fierce rivalry of the [[Jets\u2013Patriots rivalry|Jets and Patriots]. Adams apologized and let the Patriots mascot tackle him back.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gardner |first1=Steve |title=Jets' Jamal Adams crushes Patriots mascot at Pro Bowl event, says he was 'just having fun' |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2019/01/24/jets-jamal-adams-tackles-patriots-mascot-hospitalized/2669326002/ |website=USA TODAY |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAdams was also named Second-team AP All-Pro during this season. On December 28, Adams was named Curtis Martin Team MVP.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lange |first1=Randy |title=Jamal Adams Named Jets' 2018 Curtis Martin Team MVP |url=https://www.newyorkjets.com/news/jamal-adams-named-jets-2018-curtis-martin-team-mvp |website=newyorkjets.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=December 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019===\nBefore the [[2019 NFL season|2019 season]], Adams was ranked at 37th place as part of the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2019|NFL Top 100 2019]] list.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jamal Adams Named No. 37 on NFL Top 100 List |url=https://www.newyorkjets.com/news/jamal-adams-named-no-37-on-nfl-top-100-list |website=newyorkjets.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=July 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn September 18, 2019, Adams was fined $21,000 for a hit he made on [[Baker Mayfield]] on ''[[Monday Night Football]]'' against the [[2019 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]] in Week 2.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bergman |first1=Jeremy |title=NFL confirms Jets' Jamal Adams will be fined for late hit |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001056654/article/nfl-confirms-jets-jamal-adams-will-be-fined-for-late-hit |website=NFL.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=September 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Abdeldaiem |first1=Alaa |title=Jamal Adams Says NFL is 'a Damn Joke' After Being Fined for Hit on Baker Mayfield |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2019/09/19/jets-jamal-adams-rips-league-fine-hit-baker-mayfield-browns |website=Sports Illustrated |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=September 18, 2019}}</ref> In Week 3 versus the [[2019 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]], Adams recorded a 61-yard pick six off rookie quarterback [[Jarrett Stidham]] in the 30\u201314 loss. This was Adams' first interception of the season and his first career pick six.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127861 |title=Brady, Patriots defense shine in 30-14 win over Jets |date=September 22, 2019 |website=espn.com |access-date=September 22, 2019}}</ref> On October 10, Adams had his previous fine rescinded after winning an appeal.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Patra |first1=Kevin |title=Jamal Adams wins appeal of fine for hit on Mayfield |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001064167/article/jamal-adams-wins-appeal-of-fine-for-hit-on-mayfield |website=NFL.com |accessdate=October 10, 2019 |date=October 10, 2019}}</ref> In Week 10 against the [[2019 New York Giants season|New York Giants]], Adams recorded a team-high nine tackles and sacked [[Daniel Jones (American football)|Daniel Jones]] twice, one of which was a strip sack that he forced and returned for a 25-yard touchdown, as the Jets won 34\u201327 win.<ref>{{cite web |title=Eww York: Darnold, Jets hold on to beat Jones, Giants 34-27 |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127952 |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=November 10, 2019 |date=November 10, 2019}}</ref> He was named the AFC Defensive Player of the Week for his performance.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bergman |first1=Jeremy |title=Jamal Adams, Jadeveon Clowney among Players of the Week |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001076380/article/jamal-adams-jadeveon-clowney-among-players-of-the-week |website=NFL.com |accessdate=November 13, 2019 |date=November 13, 2019}}</ref> During Week 11 versus the [[2019 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]], Adams finished with three sacks as the Jets won 34\u201317.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sam Darnold throws 4 TD passes, Jets rout Redskins 34-17 |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128086 |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=November 17, 2019}}</ref> During a game versus the [[2019 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]], Adams suffered an ankle injury at the start of the game.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Vasquez |first1=Andy |title=NY Jets' Jamal Adams emotional after suffering foot injury in loss to Bengals |url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/sports/nfl/jets/2019/12/01/ny-jets-jamal-adams-emotional-after-suffering-injury-bengals-loss/4331362002/ |website=North Jersey |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=December 1, 2019}}</ref> He played the entire game and had to miss the next two weeks due to this injury. He came back from his injury in Week 16 against the [[2019 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]] in the Jets' 16\u201310 win.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lange |first1=Randy |title=Jamal Adams, Marcus Maye, Jets D Win the Battle vs. the Steelers |url=https://www.newyorkjets.com/news/jamal-adams-marcus-maye-jets-d-win-the-battle-vs-the-steelers |website=newyorkjets.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=December 22, 2019}}</ref> At the end of the season, he was named to his second consecutive Pro Bowl and was honored with his first career First-Team AP selection.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Landis |first1=Olivia |title=Jamal Adams Is Pro Bowl Bound For a Second Consecutive Year |url=https://www.newyorkjets.com/news/jamal-adams-is-pro-bowl-bound-for-a-second-consecutive-year |website=newyorkjets.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=December 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Greenberg |first1=Ethan |title=Jets S Jamal Adams Named First Team All-Pro |url=https://www.newyorkjets.com/news/jets-s-jamal-adams-named-first-team-all-pro |website=newyorkjets.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=January 3, 2020}}</ref> Adams also earned his second Curtis Martin Team MVP for the second straight year.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lange |first1=Randy |title=Jamal Adams Receives 2nd Consecutive Curtis Martin Team MVP Award |url=https://www.newyorkjets.com/news/jamal-adams-receives-2nd-consecutive-curtis-martin-team-mvp-award |website=newyorkjets.com |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=December 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Regular season===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n! colspan=\"2\"|Games\n! colspan=\"4\"|Tackles\n! colspan=\"6\"|Interceptions\n! colspan=\"2\"|Fumbles\n|-\n! GP !! GS !! Comb !! Solo !! Ast !! Sck !! PDef !! Int !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! FF !! FR\n|-\n! [[2017 NFL season|2017]] !! [[2017 New York Jets season|NYJ]]\n| 16 || 16 || 83 || 63 || 20 || 2.0 || 6 || \u2014 || \u2014 || 0.0 || \u2014 || \u2014 || 1 || 2\n|-\n! [[2018 NFL season|2018]] !! [[2018 New York Jets season|NYJ]]\n| 16 || 16 || 115 || 86 || 29 || 3.5 || 12 || 1 || 38 || 38.0 || 38 || 0 || 3 || 1\n|-\n! [[2019 NFL season|2019]] !! [[2019 New York Jets season|NYJ]]\n| 14 || 14 || 75 || 61 || 14 || 6.5 || 7 || 1 || 61 || 61.0 || 61T || 1 || 2 || 1\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Career !! 46 !! 46 !! 273 !! 210 !! 63 !! 12.0 !! 25 !! 2 !! 99 !! 49.5 !! 61 !! 1 !! 6 !! 4\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\nHis father, running back [[George Adams (American football)|George Adams]], played in the [[National Football League]] (NFL) from 1985 to 1991.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rodrigue |first1=Marcus |last2=Mickles |first2=Sheldon |last3=Rabalais |first3=Scott |title=New York connections: LSU safety Jamal Adams has some |url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_18cd519d-2025-57cc-a392-b255def92185.html |website=The Advocate |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=October 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Footballstats |nfl=2557979 |pfr=A/AdamJa00}}\n* [http://www.lsusports.net/ViewArticle.dbml?ATCLID=209392663 LSU Tigers bio]\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{New York Jets roster navbox}}\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{2017 NFL Draft}}\n{{JetsFirstPick}}\n{{Jets2017DraftPicks}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adams, Jamal}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football safeties]]\n[[Category:LSU Tigers football players]]\n[[Category:New York Jets players]]\n[[Category:People from Carrollton, Texas]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Texas]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from the Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex]]\n", "name_user": "108.7.229.154", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jamal_Adams"}
{"title_page": "Radio Poland", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox Network\n| name                = Radio Poland\n| logo                = \n| country             = {{POL}}\n| network_type        = [[international broadcasting]]\n| available           = global\n| owner               = [[Polskie Radio]]\n| key_people          = ''Danuta Isler'' (English Service Editor)\n| launch_date         = 1936\n| past_names          = Radio Polonia, PR5\n| website             = http://external.polskieradio.pl/<br>English language website http://thenews.pl\n|}}\n\n'''Radio Poland''' (until January 2007 as '''Radio Polonia''', later \"Polish Radio External Service\" ({{lang-pl|Polskie Radio dla Zagranicy}}), in Polish legislation also named as Polskie Radio Program V)  is the official [[international broadcasting]] station of [[Poland]]. \n\nRadio Poland is a part of Poland\u2019s public radio network - [[Polish Radio]]. Its aim is to broadcast programs on developments in [[Poland]], Polish foreign policy, the economy, business and foreign investments. Polish Radio External Service provides objective and impartial information about [[Poland]] and its stance on international affairs. It shows Polish society, its daily life as well as scientific and cultural achievements. Polish Radio External Service ended their English language shortwave broadcasts in 2012 and announced that they would be ceasing all shortwave transmissions on 27 October 2013, from which point they will only be broadcasting over the internet and through partnerships such as the [[World Radio Network]].<ref>http://swling.com/blog/2013/10/polish-radio-external-service-abandons-shortwave/</ref>.\n\n==History==\n\n*1936 \u2013 Polish Radio launches [[shortwave]] broadcasts of brief programmes in [[English language|English]] and [[Polish language|Polish]]\n*1945 \u2013 after the end of World War 2, the shortwave channel Warszawa III resumes external broadcasts \n*1959 - Polish Radio starts broadcasting in [[Esperanto]]\n*1990 \u2013 Polish Radio starts broadcasting for [[Ukraine]], [[Belarus]], [[Lithuania]], [[Latvia]] and [[Estonia]] \n*2000 \u2013 Radio Polonia begins daily Real Audio broadcasts in several languages via the World Radio Network\n*2007 - Radio Polonia changed name into Polish Radio External Service\n*2012 - English language shortwave transmissions end. \n*2013 - Remaining shortwave services close on 27 October.\n*2014 - Polish Radio External Service changed name into Radio Poland\n\n==Programmes==\n\nRadio Poland broadcast in six languages: [[Polish language|Polish]], [[English language|English]], [[German language|German]], [[Russian language|Russian]], [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]] and [[Belarusian language|Belarusian]] (with various amount of programming, for example English is available 24 hours a day while German 90 minutes a day). There is a [[Hebrew language]] programming, Kol Polin,<ref>[http://www.kolpolin.pl/]</ref> which includes a weekly Yiddish-language broadcast called Naye Khvalyes (\"New Waves\"). <ref>[http://yiddish-sources.com/naye-khvalyes-yiddish-radio \"Naye Khvalyes Yiddish Radio\"]</ref>\n\nShortwave transmissions were reduced between 2007 and 2012 and by 2013 PRES was broadcasting two times a day with programmes in Polish, Belarusian and Russian. On 27 October 2013 all shortwave transmissions ceased and PRES became an online only entity.\n\nRadio Poland brings:\n\n* news bulletins\n* news analysis\n* press reviews\n* correspondent\u2019s dispatches\n* interviews and discussions\n* features\nEnglish service broadcast more various programming, including quizzes, chart shows and historical programming.\n\n==Listen==\nListeners in Europe can tune in via satellite on Eutelsat 13 E, 10892&nbsp;MHz, FEC 3/4, SR 27500, Horizontal, PID audio 0119\n\nPolish Radio External Service can be heard in [[English language|English]] on the World Radio Network (WRN) through terrestrial relays, on cable and via satellite.\n\nOn cable: PR ES in [[English language|English]] is also available to 4.5 million homes on cable in [[London]], [[Dublin]], [[Berlin]], [[Amsterdam]], [[Brussels]], [[Vienna]], [[Strassburg]], [[Geneva]], [[Tokyo]], [[Washington D.C.]] and many other cities. You can also hear it on hotel cable in the [[Netherlands]] and [[Hong Kong]].\n\n===Internet===\n\n*\"Radio Poland - English Service\"   (English)\n\n48 kbit/s aac+:<br/>\nhttp://player.polskieradio.pl/-5<br/>\nhttp://stream85.polskieradio.pl/pr5/pr5.sdp/playlist.m3u8<br/>\nrtmp://stream85.polskieradio.pl/pr5/pr5.sdp<br/>\nhttp://player.polskieradio.pl/-15<br/>\nhttp://stream85.polskieradio.pl/pr5/pr5_ang.sdp/playlist.m3u8<br/>\nrtmp://stream85.polskieradio.pl/pr5/pr5_ang.sdp<br/>\nhttp://mp3.polskieradio.pl:8958<br/>\nhttp://stream3.polskieradio.pl:8958\n\n48 kbit/s wma10:<br/>\nmms://stream.polskieradio.pl/zagranica_wma10<br/>\nmms://stream1.polskieradio.pl/zagranica_wma10\n\n96 kbit/s mp3:<br/>\nhttp://mp3.polskieradio.pl:8908<br/>\nhttp://stream3.polskieradio.pl:8908\n\n96 kbit/s wma9:<br/>\nmms://stream.polskieradio.pl/zagranica<br/>\nmms://stream1.polskieradio.pl/zagranica\n\n*\"Radio Poland DAB+\"   (Belarusian, English, Ukrainian, Russian)\n\n48 kbit/s aac+:<br/>\nhttp://player.polskieradio.pl/-13<br/>\nhttp://stream85.polskieradio.pl/pr5/pr5_dab.sdp/playlist.m3u8<br/>\nrtmp://stream85.polskieradio.pl/pr5/pr5_dab.sdp\n\n48 kbit/s wma10:<br/>\nmms://stream.polskieradio.pl/zagranica_dab_wma10<br/>\nmms://stream1.polskieradio.pl/zagranica_dab_wma10\n\n96 kbit/s mp3:<br/>\nhttp://mp3.polskieradio.pl:8912<br/>\nhttp://stream3.polskieradio.pl:8912\n\n96 kbit/s wma9:<br/>\nmms://stream.polskieradio.pl/zagranica_dab_wma9<br/>\nmms://stream1.polskieradio.pl/zagranica_dab_wma9\n\n*\"Radio Poland East\" / \"\u0420\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043e \u041f\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0430\"   (Belarusian, Polish, Russian, Ukrainian)\n\n48 kbit/s aac+:<br/>\nhttp://player.polskieradio.pl/-16<br/>\nhttp://stream85.polskieradio.pl/pr5/pr5_wsch.sdp/playlist.m3u8<br/>\nrtmp://stream85.polskieradio.pl/pr5/pr5_wsch.sdp<br/>\nhttp://mp3.polskieradio.pl:8964<br/>\nhttp://stream3.polskieradio.pl:8964\n\n96 kbit/s wma10:<br/>\nmms://stream.polskieradio.pl/pr5_wsch_wma10<br/>\nmms://stream1.polskieradio.pl/pr5_wsch_wma10\n\n96 kbit/s mp3:<br/>\nhttp://mp3.polskieradio.pl:8914<br/>\nhttp://stream3.polskieradio.pl:8914\n\n96 kbit/s wma9:<br/>\nmms://stream.polskieradio.pl/pr5_wsch<br/>\nmms://stream1.polskieradio.pl/pr5_wsch\n\n===WRN satellite relays===\n\n*Europe\n\nIn [[English language|English]] WRN Europe \nEutelsat 28A 28.5\u00b0E SKY digital<br/>\nIn [[English language|English]] WRN English [[Hot Bird]] 13\u00b0E, 12.597&nbsp;GHz\n\n*North America\n\nIn [[English language|English]]\n[[Telstar]] 5 97\u00b0 W, 12.177&nbsp;GHz, pol. V\n\n*Asia, Australia \nIn [[English language|English]]\n[[AsiaSat]] 100.5\u00b0 E, 4.000&nbsp;GHz, \nEuropean Bouquet package\n\n*Africa \nIn [[English language|English]]\n[[PanAmSat]] 4 68.5\u00b0 E, Multichoice package\n\n===WRN terrestrial relays===\n\n====Europe====\n:''In Belarusian:'' \n*Poland - DAB+ network - Radio Poland DAB+ (15:30-16:00 CET)\n*Lithuania - Vilnius - Radio znad Wilii 103.8 FM (5:00-6:00, 23:30-0:00 local time)\n*Belarus, Lithuania - medium wave - Radio Baltic Waves 1386&nbsp;kHz (Sitkunai, Kaunas County, Lithuania, 75&nbsp;kW) (4:00-5:00 UTC - in winter & summer)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.evrel.ewf.uni-erlangen.de/pesc/peaceradio-BLR.html|title=Radio for Peace, Democracy and Human Rights|last=Biener|first=Hansj\u00f6rg|date=|year=2009|publisher=[[University of Erlangen\u2013Nuremberg]]|language=en|url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20170909103534/http://www.evrel.ewf.uni-erlangen.de/pesc/peaceradio-BLR.html|archivedate=2017-09-09|accessdate=2020-04-03|dead-url=yes}}</ref>\n:''In English:''\n*Poland - DAB+ network - Radio Poland DAB+\n*United Kingdom - London - Radio Spectrum DAB ONE (19:00-20:00 local time)\n*Ireland \u2013 RTE Radio 1 Extra (Sunday 19:00-20:00 local time)\n:''In Polish:''\n*Lithuania - Vilnius - Radio znad Wilii 103.8 FM (18:30-19:00, 23:00-23:30 local time)\n*Ukraine - Lviv - Radio Nezalezhnist 106.7 FM (18:30-19:00 local time)\n:''In Russian:''\n*Poland - DAB+ network - Radio Poland DAB+\n*Kaliningrad Oblast (Russia), West Russia, Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania, Belarus - medium wave - Radio Baltic Waves 1386&nbsp;kHz (Sitkunai, Kaunas County, Lithuania, 75&nbsp;kW) (16:30-17:30 UTC - in winter & summer)\n*South Russia, Georgia, Armenia, Azerbaijan - medium wave - Radio Poland 1395&nbsp;kHz (Noratus, Yerevan Country, Armenia, 500&nbsp;kW) (18:30-19:30 UTC - in winter & summer)\n*Russia - Moscow - WRN Russian 738&nbsp;kHz (Kurkino, North-Western Administrative Okrug of Moscow, 5&nbsp;kW) (17.00-17:30, 20.00-20:30, 21.00-21:30, 0.30-1:00, 5.00-5:30, 9.00-9:30, 12.30-13:00 local time)\n:''In Ukrainian:''\n*Poland - DAB+ network - Radio Poland DAB+ (19:30-20:00, 21:30-22:00, 0:30-1:00 CET)\n*Poland - Radio Rzeszow (Tuesday-Friday 01:05-01:35 CET)\n*Ukraine - Era FM (19:30-20:00 local time)\n*Donbass and Crimea  - medium wave - Radio Poland 1395&nbsp;kHz (Noratus, Yerevan Country, Armenia, 500&nbsp;kW) (19:30-20:00 UTC - in winter & summer)\n\n====North America====\n:''In English:''\nKEDM 90.3FM, University of Louisiana, Monroe;\nKORD 730AM, Concordia College, MN;\nKRVM 91.9 FM, Eugene, OR;\nKSFC 91.9FM, Spokane, WA;\nKTRU 91.7FM, Rice University, Houston, TX;\nWDWN 89.1FM, Cayuga Community Coll., Auburn, NY;\nWGHR 100.7FM, Atlanta, GA;\nWLTL 88.0FM, Le Grange, IL;\nWMCO 90.7FM, New Concord, OH;\nWQUB 90.3 FM, Quincy, IL;\nWRLC 91.7 FM, Lycoming College, Williamsport, PA;\nWUEV 91.5FM, University of Evansville, IN;\nWVUD 91.3FM, University of Delaware;\nWWHS 92.1FM, Hampden-Sydney College, VA;\nWXPR 97.1FM, Rhinelander, WI;\nWFNP 88.7 FM, New Paltz, NY;\nWRFU-LP 104.5 FM, Urbana, IL;\nKXOT 91.7 FM, Seattle, WA;\nWDIY 88.1 FM, Bethlehem, PA;\nKOHS 91.7 FM, Orem, UT.\nUS HD radio:\nTulsa Public Radio: KWGS 89.5 FM, Tulsa, OK;\nKRCL 90.9 FM, Salt Lake City, UT;\nWLNZ 89.7 FM, Lansing, MI;\nService Electric Cable TV, Sussex C., NJ;\nSCOLA, 300 College systems throughout the USA, Channel 1.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Polskie Radio]], the Polish publicly funded radio broadcaster\n*[[Eastern Bloc information dissemination]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://external.polskieradio.pl/ Polish Radio External Service Website] {{in lang|pl|en|de|ru|uk|be|he}}\n* [http://external.polskieradio.pl/Player?id=-5 Listen to Polish Radio External Service online] {{in lang|pl|en|ru|uk|be}}\n\n{{Radio stations in Poland}}\n{{World Radio Network}}\n{{Eastern Bloc media}}\n{{Telecommunications}}\n{{coord missing|Poland}}\n\n[[Category:Polskie Radio]]\n[[Category:International broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1936]]\n[[Category:1936 establishments in Poland]]\n[[Category:Polish news websites]]\n\n[[eo:Radio Polonia]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox Network\n| name                = Radio Poland\n| logo                = \n| country             = {{POL}}\n| network_type        = [[international broadcasting]]\n| available           = global\n| owner               = [[Polskie Radio]]\n| key_people          = ''Danuta Isler'' (English Service Editor)\n| launch_date         = 1936\n| past_names          = Radio Polonia, PR5\n| website             = http://external.polskieradio.pl/<br>English language website http://thenews.pl\n|}}\n\n'''Radio Poland''' (until January 2007 as '''Radio Polonia''', later \"Polish Radio External Service\" ({{lang-pl|Polskie Radio dla Zagranicy}}), in Polish legislation also named as Polskie Radio Program V)  is the official [[international broadcasting]] station of [[Poland]]. \n\nRadio Poland is a part of Poland\u2019s public radio network - [[Polish Radio]]. Its aim is to broadcast programs on developments in [[Poland]], Polish foreign policy, the economy, business and foreign investments. Polish Radio External Service provides objective and impartial information about [[Poland]] and its stance on international affairs. It shows Polish society, its daily life as well as scientific and cultural achievements. Polish Radio External Service ended their English language shortwave broadcasts in 2012 and announced that they would be ceasing all shortwave transmissions on 27 October 2013, from which point they will only be broadcasting over the internet and through partnerships such as the [[World Radio Network]].<ref>http://swling.com/blog/2013/10/polish-radio-external-service-abandons-shortwave/</ref>.\n\n==History==\n\n*1936 \u2013 Polish Radio launches [[shortwave]] broadcasts of brief programmes in [[English language|English]] and [[Polish language|Polish]]\n*1945 \u2013 after the end of World War 2, the shortwave channel Warszawa III resumes external broadcasts \n*1959 - Polish Radio starts broadcasting in [[Esperanto]]\n*1990 \u2013 Polish Radio starts broadcasting for [[Ukraine]], [[Belarus]], [[Lithuania]], [[Latvia]] and [[Estonia]] \n*2000 \u2013 Radio Polonia begins daily Real Audio broadcasts in several languages via the World Radio Network\n*2007 - Radio Polonia changed name into Polish Radio External Service\n*2012 - English language shortwave transmissions end. \n*2013 - Remaining shortwave services close on 27 October.\n*2014 - Polish Radio External Service changed name into Radio Poland\n\n==Programmes==\n\nRadio Poland broadcast in six languages: [[Polish language|Polish]], [[English language|English]], [[German language|German]], [[Russian language|Russian]], [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]] and [[Belarusian language|Belarusian]] (with various amount of programming, for example English is available 24 hours a day while German 90 minutes a day). There is a [[Hebrew language]] programming, Kol Polin,<ref>[http://www.kolpolin.pl/]</ref> which includes a weekly Yiddish-language broadcast called Naye Khvalyes (\"New Waves\"). <ref>[http://yiddish-sources.com/naye-khvalyes-yiddish-radio \"Naye Khvalyes Yiddish Radio\"]</ref>\n\nShortwave transmissions were reduced between 2007 and 2012 and by 2013 PRES was broadcasting two times a day with programmes in Polish, Belarusian and Russian. On 27 October 2013 all shortwave transmissions ceased and PRES became an online only entity.\n\nRadio Poland brings:\n\n* news bulletins\n* news analysis\n* press reviews\n* correspondent\u2019s dispatches\n* interviews and discussions\n* features\nEnglish service broadcast more various programming, including quizzes, chart shows and historical programming.\n\n==Listen==\nListeners in Europe can tune in via satellite on Eutelsat 13 E, 10892&nbsp;MHz, FEC 3/4, SR 27500, Horizontal, PID audio 0119\n\nPolish Radio External Service can be heard in [[English language|English]] on the World Radio Network (WRN) through terrestrial relays, on cable and via satellite.\n\nOn cable: PR ES in [[English language|English]] is also available to 4.5 million homes on cable in [[London]], [[Dublin]], [[Berlin]], [[Amsterdam]], [[Brussels]], [[Vienna]], [[Strassburg]], [[Geneva]], [[Tokyo]], [[Washington D.C.]] and many other cities. You can also hear it on hotel cable in the [[Netherlands]] and [[Hong Kong]].\n\n===Internet===\n\n*\"Radio Poland - English Service\"   (English)\n\n48 kbit/s aac+:<br/>\nhttp://player.polskieradio.pl/-5<br/>\nhttp://stream85.polskieradio.pl/pr5/pr5.sdp/playlist.m3u8<br/>\nrtmp://stream85.polskieradio.pl/pr5/pr5.sdp<br/>\nhttp://player.polskieradio.pl/-15<br/>\nhttp://stream85.polskieradio.pl/pr5/pr5_ang.sdp/playlist.m3u8<br/>\nrtmp://stream85.polskieradio.pl/pr5/pr5_ang.sdp<br/>\nhttp://mp3.polskieradio.pl:8958<br/>\nhttp://stream3.polskieradio.pl:8958\n\n48 kbit/s wma10:<br/>\nmms://stream.polskieradio.pl/zagranica_wma10<br/>\nmms://stream1.polskieradio.pl/zagranica_wma10\n\n96 kbit/s mp3:<br/>\nhttp://mp3.polskieradio.pl:8908<br/>\nhttp://stream3.polskieradio.pl:8908\n\n96 kbit/s wma9: