[[Aquatics at the 2007 Southeast Asian Games|1 m springboard]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Aquatics at the 2007 Southeast Asian Games|2007 Nakhon Ratchasima]]|[[Aquatics at the 2007 Southeast Asian Games|3 m synchro]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Aquatics at the 2009 Southeast Asian Games|2009 Vientiane]]|[[Aquatics at the 2009 Southeast Asian Games|10 m synchro]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Aquatics at the 2009 Southeast Asian Games|2009 Vientiane]]|[[Aquatics at the 2009 Southeast Asian Games|3 m synchro]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Aquatics at the 2011 Southeast Asian Games|2011 Palembang]]|[[Aquatics at the 2011 Southeast Asian Games|3 m synchro]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Aquatics at the 2011 Southeast Asian Games|2011 Palembang]]|[[Aquatics at the 2011 Southeast Asian Games|10 m synchro]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Aquatics at the 2013 Southeast Asian Games|2013 Naypyidaw]]|[[Aquatics at the 2013 Southeast Asian Games|10 m synchro]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Diving at the 2015 Southeast Asian Games| 2015 Singapore ]]|[[Diving at the 2015 Southeast Asian Games|10 m synchro]]}} \n{{MedalGold|[[Diving at the 2017 Southeast Asian Games| 2017 Kuala Lumpur ]]|[[Diving at the 2017 Southeast Asian Games|10m synchro]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Diving at the 2017 Southeast Asian Games| 2017 Kuala Lumpur ]]|[[Diving at the 2017  Southeast Asian Games|10m mixed synchro]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|1999 Brunei|3 m springboard}}\n{{MedalSilver|2003 Hanoi|10 m synchro}}\n{{MedalSilver|2003 Hanoi|3 m synchro}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[Aquatics at the 2005 Southeast Asian Games|2005 Manila]]|[[Aquatics at the 2005 Southeast Asian Games|1 m springboard]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[Aquatics at the 2007 Southeast Asian Games|2007 Nakhon Ratchasima]]|[[Aquatics at the 2007 Southeast Asian Games|3 m springboard]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|1999 Brunei|10 m platform}}\n{{MedalBronze|2003 Hanoi|3 m springboard}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[Aquatics at the 2005 Southeast Asian Games|2005 Manila]]|[[Aquatics at the 2005 Southeast Asian Games|3 m springboard]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[Aquatics at the 2005 Southeast Asian Games|2005 Manila]]|[[Aquatics at the 2005 Southeast Asian Games|3 m synchro]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[Aquatics at the 2009 Southeast Asian Games|2009 Vientiane]]|[[Aquatics at the 2009 Southeast Asian Games|3 m springboard]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Diving at the Summer Universiade|Universiade]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[2011 Summer Universiade|2011 Shenzhen]] | [[Diving at the 2011 Summer Universiade|10 m synchro]]}}\n}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Liang (surname)|Leong]]}}\n'''Leong Mun Yee''' ({{zh|s=\u6881\u654f\u55bb|p=Li\u00e1ng M\u01d0ny\u00f9}}, born 4 December 1984) is a Malaysian [[Diving (sport)|diver]]. She competed at the 2000, 2004, 2008 and 2012 Olympics with the best result of seventh place in the [[Diving at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's synchronized 10 metre platform|10 m synchronised platform event]] in 2012. Her appearance at the 2008 Summer Olympics made her the first Malaysian diver to compete at three Olympics.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url = http://g2014results.thecgf.com/athlete/diving/1032783/l_mun_yee.html|title = Leong Mun Yee biography \u2013 2014 Commonwealth Games|date = 8 August 2014|accessdate = 13 September 2015|website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>  The bronze medal that she and [[Pandelela Rinong]] won at the 2009 World Championships was the first World Championship medal for Malaysia.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nShe was originally a swimmer but switched to diving at the age of 10 as part of Malaysia's programme to prepare a diving team for the [[1998 Commonwealth Games]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nShe graduated with a degree in communication from [[Universiti Putra Malaysia]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{FINA}}\n*{{Sports-reference}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leong, Mun Yee}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Ipoh]]\n[[Category:Malaysian people of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Malaysian sportswomen]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople of Chinese descent]]\n